title: For Sale:  Warning - Counterfeit Bills!
postcontent:
Around Nov. 27th I sold a mint Taurus Judge - Public Defender with a 2" barrel.  The buyer gave me $500 cash and $350 of it was in counterfeit 50's. The bank confirmed this. The buyer's driver's license seemed to check out.  He had a strange name and his middle name is Cochise.  He was born in 1978 as I remember, making him around 37 years old. He is a fairly tall - (5-10 to 6ft?), heavy-set black man. I think he drove a pickup truck.  I think he knows the bills are fake (has not responded) and he very well may have bought other guns with the fake money.  He also had real 20s and 5 dollar bills with the counterfeit 50s. 

Be on the alert because other buyers probably have the fake notes as well. If you have encountered this man or someone like him please let me know.  You may have some helpful clues to help find the thief. The police are working on it. Thanks for your help.

8zero4-six31-1four77

postcontent: Rifle from my father's Estate Make: Davide Pedersoli Model: Swivel Barrel Rifle Serial Numbers: (one per barrel) 73128 and 73066 Year of Manufacture: 1995 Caliber: .50 Caliber Ball Action Type: Single Lock Swivel Barrel Muzzle Loading Cap and Ball Markings: The left side of both barrels are marked with an Italian Star over “PN” black powder proof, an Italian “BB” date stamp, an Italian Star over Crest ‘Gardone’ proof, a Pedersoli logo, “BLACK POWDER ONLY / MADE IN ITALY” and “CAL. 50”. Barrel Length: 23 2/3” Sights / Optics: Both barrels are equipped with an orange fiber optic beaded blade. The rear sights are “U” notched leaves with two fiber optic dots adjustable for elevation and windage, screwed to the barrel. Stock Configuration & Condition: The two piece pistol grip checkered walnut stocks feature a two piece forend and a fluted butt stock with a Monte Carlo comb. No marks are visible on the stocks. The LOP measures 14 ½” from the front of the trigger to the back of the solid rubber recoil pad which is in Excellent condition. The stocks are in Excellent condition. Type of Finish: Matte Blue Finish Originality: Factory Original Bore Condition: On one side of the rifle, the barrels have some surface rust spots. The other side looks "out of the box." Overall Condition: This rifle appears to have never been used. The only marks are the surface rust spots on one side. Overall, this rifle rates in about Excellent condition. Mechanics: Per my research, this is a muzzle loading rifle with two barrels which swivel around a central pivot. Each barrel has its own percussion cap nipple. After the first barrel is fired, the hammer is moved to half cock and the barrels are rotated 180 degrees, where the second barrel locks into position. The hammer locks securely into half cock and full cock and will not fall from half cock. As I stated, this rifle looks to be brand new and never been fired. As with all previously owned firearms, a thorough cleaning may be necessary to meet your maintenance standards. Box, Paperwork & Accessories: An alloy ram rod with a brass fouling jag is installed. Per my research: During the muzzle loading era, repeating arms were an elusive technological development. Until Colt’s Patterson Revolver in 1836 and Henry’s Repeating Rifle revolving barrel assemblies were the answer. The pepperbox pistols became common during the percussion era, but revolving barrels were used on rifles as well. This Pedersoli version of the Swivel Barrel percussion rifle is just plain neat. It is a .50 caliber cap and ball rifle with two 23 2/3” barrels. After the first barrel is fired, the hammer is put into half cock and the barrels rotated 180 degrees, locking the second barrel into position. This rifle is equipped with modern, adjustable fiber optic dot sights. The barrels rotate and lock securely into position. Made with Pedersoli quality, the Swivel Barrel .50 caliber percussion rifle is in Excellent condition. Cash. Local sale only.

title: For Sale:  Ruger 10/22 50th Anniversary Design Winner rifle 22lr, SS 18.5" barrel
postcontent:
Very nice limited edition 50th Anniversary Design Contest Winner Ruger 10/22 22lr rifle, stainless steel 18.5" barrel. Black stock, two interchangeable stock pieces. Original box, lock, manual. Comes with one 10rd mag. I have additional 25 and 50 round mags available separately.

No trades. Buyer must be an Alabama resident, conceal carry permit preferred.
-----------------------------------------------
It’s got a stainless finish, an 18.5″ barrel, and a synthetic stock. But anyone familiar with the standard 10/22 will quickly notice a few key features that set this rifle apart from the usual.

The first and most distinctive feature of this 10/22 is the rear sight/scope rail combo. Most 10/22 rifles have open sights with both the front and rear mounted to the barrel. They’re quick, but not very good for precision and only adjustable for elevation. “Target” versions of the 10/22 have no sights at all, but come with a rail for mounting optics. There are some nice aftermarket adjustable aperture sights that mount to the 10/22 receiver, but most of them take up the space where the scope rail goes, so they have to be removed in order to use optics. The contest winning 10/22 offers the best of both worlds by using a picatinny rail with an integrated fully adjustable rear aperture sight. It’s complimented by a military style front sight blade protected by ears on either side.

Another stand-out feature of the design contest 10/22 is the adjustable stock, which was borrowed from the Ruger American rimfire bolt action rifles. The rear of the stock can be used with different “stock modules”; essentially, pieces that change the length of pull and the comb height. The rifle comes with one short and one tall stock piece for use with iron sights and optics respectively. The importance of a good cheek weld is often underestimated, so it’s encouraging to see a company getting on board with helping customers get the most out of their rifles when using optics.

One aspect of the new 10/22 that might confuse some people is the flash hider. Why would you want a flash hider on a .22 rifle? It’s a valid question, but according to Gary, the key is not to think of it as a flash hider, but as a “mud guard”. Apparently it’s a common problem for rookie shooters in Appleseed clinics to accidentally dip their muzzles into the ground when practicing the prone position. This can lead to dangerous barrel obstructions, or even more tragic, unsightly scratches and dings on the muzzle. From Ruger’s perspective, the flash hider is a great addition because it’s an easy way to make sure that potential customers notice the barrel is threaded… potential customers like me who are going to immediately toss that flash hider aside and throw a suppressor on there.

Check out http://www.luckygunner.com/lounge/ruger-anniversary-design-contest-winner/ for more pictures and information.
